[Date: Tue, 10 Jan 2023 23:24:17 +0000 (UTC) From: Patients Know Best To: Cz Patient 1 Message-ID: <444602532.203.1673393057391@8886d02463e2> Subject: You are connected to a new team at Org D MIME-Version: 1.0 Content-Type: multipart/mixed; boundary="----=_Part_200_1521693707.1673393057387" ------=_Part_200_1521693707.1673393057387 Content-Type: multipart/related; boundary="----=_Part_201_1242359560.1673393057387" ------=_Part_201_1242359560.1673393057387 Content-Type: multipart/alternative; boundary="----=_Part_202_554330734.1673393057387" ------=_Part_202_554330734.1673393057387 Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8 Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit Dear Cz, Org D has connected your Patients Know Best (PKB) record to a new team that is, or has been, working with you. The team's name is Team DY. Why has this happened? Team DY holds information about you or for you. PKB links you to the team so you can see information about you (such as test results) and information for you (such as library links). In some cases, you can interact with the team (through secure messaging). Your PKB record is a single place to store information from you, your health professionals and your medical devices. To learn more about PKB, please visit our website: http://pkb-frontend-4 What happens next? When you have registered, if Team DY sends you information, PKB will notify you by email. What if I do not know the Org D or Team DY team? Sometimes you may see an organisation or team name that is unfamiliar to you. This often happens when health care services share resources for managing their patients' or service users' care. For example, GPs and hospitals sometimes share laboratory systems for your test results, and therefore you may receive data from an organisation you've never been to. How do I know what information they have about me and what they can see about me? The information they have about you or for you so far is in your PKB record. You can log in to see it now: http://pkb-frontend-4 This team is able to see information in your record marked with general privacy. This team is not able to see information marked with social, mental and sexual privacy. You can change the level of access they have at any time by clicking this link (http://pkb-frontend-4/patient/myConsentTeam.action?tab=invitations&subTab=myClinicians) and adjusting their settings, you can read more in the PKB manual (https://manual.patientsknowbest.com/patient/sharing). Please do not reply to this email; this address is not monitored. Log into your record to see your medical information and manage your care: http://pkb-frontend-4 Yours, Patients Know Best Help Team w: www.patientsknowbest.com/contact-us e: help@pkbtest.com ------=_Part_202_554330734.1673393057387 Content-Type: text/html;charset=UTF-8 Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit

Dear Cz,

Org D has connected your Patients Know Best (PKB) record to a new team that is, or has been, working with you. The team's name is Team DY.

Why has this happened?
Team DY holds information about you or for you. PKB links you to the team so you can see information about you (such as test results) and information for you (such as library links). In some cases, you can interact with the team (through secure messaging).

PKB links you to the team so you can see information about you (such as test results) and information for you (such as library links). In some cases, you can interact with the team (through secure messaging). Your PKB record is a single place to store information from you, your health professionals and your medical devices. To learn more about PKB, please visit our website: http://pkb-frontend-4 What happens next? When you have registered, if Team DY sends you information, PKB will notify you by email. Dear Cz,

Org D has connected your Patients Know Best (PKB) record to a new team that is, or has been, working with you. The team's name is Team DY.

Why has this happened?
Team DY holds information about you or for you. PKB links you to the team so you can see information about you (such as test results) and information for you (such as library links). In some cases, you can interact with the team (through secure messaging).

Your PKB record is a single place to store information from you, your health professionals and your medical devices. To learn more about PKB, please visit our website.

What happens next?
When you have registered, if Team DY sends you information, PKB will notify you by email.

What if I do not know the Org D or Team DY team?
Sometimes you may see an organisation or team name that is unfamiliar to you. This often happens when health care services share resources for managing their patients' or service users' care. For example, GPs and hospitals sometimes share laboratory systems for your test results, and therefore you may receive data from an organisation you've never been to.

How do I know what information they have about me and what they can see about me?
The information they have about you or for you so far is in your PKB record. You can log in to see it now.

This team is able to see information in your record marked with social privacy. This team is not able to see information marked with general, mental and sexual privacy.

You can change the level of access they have at any time by clicking this link and adjusting their settings, you can read more in the PKB manual.

Please do not reply to this email; this address is not monitored. Log into your record to see your medical information and manage your care.

Yours,

Patients Know Best Help Team

Dear Cz,

Org D has connected your Patients Know Best (PKB) record to a new team that is, or has been, working with you. The team's name is Team DY.

Why has this happened?
Team DY holds information about you or for you. PKB links you to the team so you can see information about you (such as test results) and information for you (such as library links). In some cases, you can interact with the team (through secure messaging).

Your PKB record is a single place to store information from you, your health professionals and your medical devices. To learn more about PKB, please visit our website.

What happens next?
When you have registered, if Team DY sends you information, PKB will notify you by email.

What if I do not know the Org D or Team DY team?
Sometimes you may see an organisation or team name that is unfamiliar to you. This often happens when health care services share resources for managing their patients' or service users' care. For example, GPs and hospitals sometimes share laboratory systems for your test results, and therefore you may receive data from an organisation you've never been to.

How do I know what information they have about me and what they can see about me?
The information they have about you or for you so far is in your PKB record. You can log in to see it now.

This team is able to see information in your record marked with mental privacy. This team is not able to see information marked with general, social and sexual privacy.

You can change the level of access they have at any time by clicking this link and adjusting their settings, you can read more in the PKB manual.

Please do not reply to this email; this address is not monitored. Log into your record to see your medical information and manage your care.

Yours,

Patients Know Best Help Team

[Date: Tue, 10 Jan 2023 23:25:07 +0000 (UTC) From: Patients Know Best To: Cz Patient 2 Message-ID: <1106155825.287.1673393107634@8886d02463e2> Subject: You are connected to a new team at Org D MIME-Version: 1.0 Content-Type: multipart/mixed; boundary="----=_Part_284_491905639.1673393107630" ------=_Part_284_491905639.1673393107630 Content-Type: multipart/related; boundary="----=_Part_285_1015081943.1673393107630" ------=_Part_285_1015081943.1673393107630 Content-Type: multipart/alternative; boundary="----=_Part_286_1186260050.1673393107630" ------=_Part_286_1186260050.1673393107630 Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8 Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit Dear Cz, Org D has connected your Patients Know Best (PKB) record to a new team that is, or has been, working with you. The team's name is Team DY. Why has this happened? Team DY holds information about you or for you. PKB links you to the team so you can see information about you (such as test results) and information for you (such as library links). In some cases, you can interact with the team (through secure messaging). Your PKB record is a single place to store information from you, your health professionals and your medical devices. To learn more about PKB, please visit our website: http://pkb-frontend-4 What happens next? When you have registered, if Team DY sends you information, PKB will notify you by email. What if I do not know the Org D or Team DY team? Sometimes you may see an organisation or team name that is unfamiliar to you. This often happens when health care services share resources for managing their patients' or service users' care. For example, GPs and hospitals sometimes share laboratory systems for your test results, and therefore you may receive data from an organisation you've never been to. How do I know what information they have about me and what they can see about me? The information they have about you or for you so far is in your PKB record. Please do not reply to this email; this address is not monitored. Dear Cz,

Org D has connected your Patients Know Best (PKB) record to a new team that is, or has been, working with you. The team's name is Team DY.

Why has this happened?
Team DY holds information about you or for you. PKB links you to the team so you can see information about you (such as test results) and information for you (such as library links). In some cases, you can interact with the team (through secure messaging).

Your PKB record is a single place to store information from you, your health professionals and your medical devices. To learn more about PKB, please visit our website.

What happens next?
When you have registered, if Team DY sends you information, PKB will notify you by email.

What if I do not know the Org D or Team DY team?
Sometimes you may see an organisation or team name that is unfamiliar to you. This often happens when health care services share resources for managing their patients' or service users' care. For example, GPs and hospitals sometimes share laboratory systems for your test results, and therefore you may receive data from an organisation you've never been to.

How do I know what information they have about me and what they can see about me?
The information they have about you or for you so far is in your PKB record. You can log in to see it now.

This team is able to see information in your record marked with sexual privacy. This team is not able to see information marked with general, social and mental privacy.

You can change the level of access they have at any time by clicking this link and adjusting their settings, you can read more in the PKB manual.

Please do not reply to this email; this address is not monitored. Log into your record to see your medical information and manage your care.

Yours,

Patients Know Best Help Team

Dear Cz,

Org D has connected your Patients Know Best (PKB) record to a new team that is, or has been, working with you. The team's name is Team DY.

Why has this happened?
Team DY holds information about you or for you. PKB links you to the team so you can see information about you (such as test results) and information for you (such as library links). In some cases, you can interact with the team (through secure messaging).

Your PKB record is a single place to store information from you, your health professionals and your medical devices. To learn more about PKB, please visit our website.

What happens next?
When you have registered, if Team DY sends you information, PKB will notify you by email.

What if I do not know the Org D or Team DY team?
Sometimes you may see an organisation or team name that is unfamiliar to you. This often happens when health care services share resources for managing their patients' or service users' care. How do I know what information they have about me and what they can see about me?
The information they have about you or for you so far is in your PKB record. You can log in to see it now.

This team is able to see information in your record marked with general and social privacy. This team is not able to see information marked with mental and sexual privacy.

You can change the level of access they have at any time by clicking this link and adjusting their settings, you can read more in the PKB manual.

Please do not reply to this email; this address is not monitored. Log into your record to see your medical information and manage your care.

Yours,

[Date: Tue, 10 Jan 2023 23:25:39 +0000 (UTC) From: Patients Know Best To: Cz Patient 2 Message-ID: <1076545962.343.1673393139660@8886d02463e2> Subject: You are connected to a new team at Org D MIME-Version: 1.0 Content-Type: multipart/mixed; boundary="----=_Part_340_1882643434.1673393139656" ------=_Part_340_1882643434.1673393139656 Content-Type: multipart/related; boundary="----=_Part_341_533592876.1673393139656" ------=_Part_341_533592876.1673393139656 Content-Type: multipart/alternative; boundary="----=_Part_342_856978339.1673393139656" ------=_Part_342_856978339.1673393139656 Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8 Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit Dear Cz, Org D has connected your Patients Know Best (PKB) record to a new team that is, or has been, working with you. The team's name is Team DY. Why has this happened? Team DY holds information about you or for you. PKB links you to the team so you can see information about you (such as test results) and information for you (such as library links). In some cases, you can interact with the team (through secure messaging). Your PKB record is a single place to store information from you, your health professionals and your medical devices. To learn more about PKB, please visit our website: http://pkb-frontend-4 What happens next? When you have registered, if Team DY sends you information, PKB will notify you by email. What if I do not know the Org D or Team DY team? Sometimes you may see an organisation or team name that is unfamiliar to you. This often happens when health care services share resources for managing their patients' or service users' care. For example, GPs and hospitals sometimes share laboratory systems for your test results, and therefore you may receive data from an organisation you've never been to. How do I know what information they have about me and what they can see about me? The information they have about you or for you so far is in your PKB record. You can log in to see it now: http://pkb-frontend-4 This team is able to see information in your record marked with general, social and mental privacy. Dear Cz,

Org D has connected your Patients Know Best (PKB) record to a new team that is, or has been, working with you. The team's name is Team DY.

Why has this happened?
Team DY holds information about you or for you. PKB links you to the team so you can see information about you (such as test results) and information for you (such as library links). In some cases, you can interact with the team (through secure messaging).

Your PKB record is a single place to store information from you, your health professionals and your medical devices. To learn more about PKB, please visit our website.

What happens next?
When you have registered, if Team DY sends you information, PKB will notify you by email.

What if I do not know the Org D or Team DY team?
Sometimes you may see an organisation or team name that is unfamiliar to you. This often happens when health care services share resources for managing their patients' or service users' care. For example, GPs and hospitals sometimes share laboratory systems for your test results, and therefore you may receive data from an organisation you've never been to.

How do I know what information they have about me and what they can see about me?
The information they have about you or for you so far is in your PKB record. You can log in to see it now.

This team is able to see information in your record marked with general, social and mental privacy. This team is not able to see information marked with sexual privacy.

You can change the level of access they have at any time by clicking this link and adjusting their settings, you can read more in the PKB manual.

Please do not reply to this email; this address is not monitored. Log into your record to see your medical information and manage your care.

Yours,

Patients Know Best Help Team

The team's name is Team DY. Why has this happened? Team DY holds information about you or for you. PKB links you to the team so you can see information about you (such as test results) and information for you (such as library links). In some cases, you can interact with the team (through secure messaging). Your PKB record is a single place to store information from you, your health professionals and your medical devices. To learn more about PKB, please visit our website: http://pkb-frontend-4 What happens next? When you have registered, if Team DY sends you information, PKB will notify you by email. What if I do not know the Org D or Team DY team? Sometimes you may see an organisation or team name that is unfamiliar to you. Dear Cz,

Org D has connected your Patients Know Best (PKB) record to a new team that is, or has been, working with you. The team's name is Team DY.

Why has this happened?
Team DY holds information about you or for you. PKB links you to the team so you can see information about you (such as test results) and information for you (such as library links). In some cases, you can interact with the team (through secure messaging).

Your PKB record is a single place to store information from you, your health professionals and your medical devices. To learn more about PKB, please visit our website.

What happens next?
When you have registered, if Team DY sends you information, PKB will notify you by email.

What if I do not know the Org D or Team DY team?
Sometimes you may see an organisation or team name that is unfamiliar to you. This often happens when health care services share resources for managing their patients' or service users' care. For example, GPs and hospitals sometimes share laboratory systems for your test results, and therefore you may receive data from an organisation you've never been to.

How do I know what information they have about me and what they can see about me?
The information they have about you or for you so far is in your PKB record. You can log in to see it now.

This team is able to see information in your record marked with general, social, mental and sexual privacy.

You can change the level of access they have at any time by clicking this link and adjusting their settings, you can read more in the PKB manual.

Please do not reply to this email; this address is not monitored. Log into your record to see your medical information and manage your care.

Yours,

Patients Know Best Help Team

Dear Az,

Org D has connected Cz's Patients Know Best (PKB) record to a new team that is, or has been, working with them. The team's name is Team DY.

Why has this happened?
Team DY holds information about or for Cz. PKB links them to the team so you can see information about them (such as test results) and information for them (such as library links). In some cases, you can interact with the team (through secure messaging).

Their PKB record is a single place to store information from you, Cz, their health professionals and their medical devices. To learn more about PKB, please visit our website.

What happens next?
When you have registered, if Team DY sends Cz information, PKB will notify you by email. If Cz has registered, they will receive an email too.

What if I do not know the Org D or Team DY team?
Sometimes you may see an organisation or team name that is unfamiliar to you. This often happens when health care services share resources for managing their patients' or service users' care. For example, GPs and hospitals sometimes share laboratory systems for test results, and therefore one can receive data from an organisation without having been there.

How do I know what information they have about Cz and what they can see in the record?
The information the team has about or for Cz so far is in their PKB record. You can log in to see it now.

This team is able to see information in their record marked with general, social, mental and sexual privacy.

You can change the level of access they have at any time by clicking this link and adjusting their settings, you can read more in the PKB manual.

You are receiving this notification because you are a carer. To log in and review the people you care for, please click this link: "http://pkb-frontend-4/patient/myDependents.action?tab=invitations&subTab=dependents"

Please do not reply to this email; this address is not monitored. Log into your record to manage your care and those whom you care for.

Yours,

Patients Know Best Help Team

parameters.name: emailContents
parameters.value:
[Date: Tue, 10 Jan 2023 23:26:11 +0000 (UTC) From: Patients Know Best To: Cz Patient 2 Message-ID: <492557699.399.1673393171377@8886d02463e2> Subject: You are connected to a new team at Org D MIME-Version: 1.0 Content-Type: multipart/mixed; boundary="----=_Part_396_1869196686.1673393171373" ------=_Part_396_1869196686.1673393171373 Content-Type: multipart/related; boundary="----=_Part_397_758618203.1673393171373" ------=_Part_397_758618203.1673393171373 Content-Type: multipart/alternative; boundary="----=_Part_398_1142299059.1673393171373" ------=_Part_398_1142299059.1673393171373 Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8 Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit Dear Cz, Org D has connected your Patients Know Best (PKB) record to a new team that is, or has been, working with you. The team's name is Team DY. Why has this happened? Team DY holds information about you or for you. PKB links you to the team so you can see information about you (such as test results) and information for you (such as library links). In some cases, you can interact with the team (through secure messaging). Your PKB record is a single place to store information from you, your health professionals and your medical devices. Dear Cz,

Org D has connected your Patients Know Best (PKB) record to a new team that is, or has been, working with you. The team's name is Team DY.

Why has this happened?
Team DY holds information about you or for you. PKB links you to the team so you can see information about you (such as test results) and information for you (such as library links). In some cases, you can interact with the team (through secure messaging).

Your PKB record is a single place to store information from you, your health professionals and your medical devices. To learn more about PKB, please visit our website.

What happens next?
When you have registered, if Team DY sends you information, PKB will notify you by email.

What if I do not know the Org D or Team DY team?
Sometimes you may see an organisation or team name that is unfamiliar to you. This often happens when health care services share resources for managing their patients' or service users' care. For example, GPs and hospitals sometimes share laboratory systems for your test results, and therefore you may receive data from an organisation you've never been to.

How do I know what information they have about me and what they can see about me?
The information they have about you or for you so far is in your PKB record. You can log in to see it now.

This team is able to see information in your record marked with social, mental and sexual privacy. This team is not able to see information marked with general privacy.

You can change the level of access they have at any time by clicking this link and adjusting their settings, you can read more in the PKB manual.

Please do not reply to this email; this address is not monitored. Log into your record to see your medical information and manage your care.

Yours,

Patients Know Best Help Team

Dear Cz,

Org D has connected your Patients Know Best (PKB) record to a new team that is, or has been, working with you. The team's name is Team DY.

Why has this happened?
Team DY holds information about you or for you. PKB links you to the team so you can see information about you (such as test results) and information for you (such as library links). In some cases, you can interact with the team (through secure messaging).

Your PKB record is a single place to store information from you, your health professionals and your medical devices. To learn more about PKB, please visit our website.

What happens next?
When you have registered, if Team DY sends you information, PKB will notify you by email.

What if I do not know the Org D or Team DY team?
Sometimes you may see an organisation or team name that is unfamiliar to you. This often happens when health care services share resources for managing their patients' or service users' care. For example, GPs and hospitals sometimes share laboratory systems for your test results, and therefore you may receive data from an organisation you've never been to.

How do I know what information they have about me and what they can see about me?
The information they have about you or for you so far is in your PKB record. You can log in to see it now.

This team is able to see information in your record marked with mental and sexual privacy. This team is not able to see information marked with general and social privacy.

You can change the level of access they have at any time by clicking this link and adjusting their settings, you can read more in the PKB manual.

Please do not reply to this email; this address is not monitored. Log into your record to see your medical information and manage your care.

Yours,

Patients Know Best Help Team

[Date: Tue, 10 Jan 2023 23:27:00 +0000 (UTC) From: Patients Know Best To: Cz Patient 2 Message-ID: <346764189.483.1673393220055@8886d02463e2> Subject: You are connected to a new team at Org D MIME-Version: 1.0 Content-Type: multipart/mixed; boundary="----=_Part_480_1144178694.1673393220050" ------=_Part_480_1144178694.1673393220050 Content-Type: multipart/related; boundary="----=_Part_481_485165713.1673393220050" ------=_Part_481_485165713.1673393220050 Content-Type: multipart/alternative; boundary="----=_Part_482_1965726959.1673393220050" ------=_Part_482_1965726959.1673393220050 Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8 Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit Dear Cz, Org D has connected your Patients Know Best (PKB) record to a new team that is, or has been, working with you. The team's name is Team DY. Why has this happened? Team DY holds information about you or for you. PKB links you to the team so you can see information about you (such as test results) and information for you (such as library links). In some cases, you can interact with the team (through secure messaging). Your PKB record is a single place to store information from you, your health professionals and your medical devices. To learn more about PKB, please visit our website: http://pkb-frontend-4 What happens next? When you have registered, if Team DY sends you information, PKB will notify you by email. What if I do not know the Org D or Team DY team? Sometimes you may see an organisation or team name that is unfamiliar to you. This often happens when health care services share resources for managing their patients' or service users' care. For example, GPs and hospitals sometimes share laboratory systems for your test results, and therefore you may receive data from an organisation you've never been to. How do I know what information they have about me and what they can see about me? The information they have about you or for you so far is in your PKB record. You can log in to see it now: http://pkb-frontend-4 This team is not able to see any other information in your record except information the team has added themselves. You can change the level of access they have at any time by clicking this link (http://pkb-frontend-4/patient/myConsentTeam.action?tab=invitations&subTab=myClinicians) and adjusting their settings, you can read more in the PKB manual (https://manual.patientsknowbest.com/patient/sharing). Please do not reply to this email; this address is not monitored. Log into your record to see your medical information and manage your care: http://pkb-frontend-4 Yours, Patients Know Best Help Team w: www.patientsknowbest.com/contact-us e: help@pkbtest.com ------=_Part_482_1965726959.1673393220050 Content-Type: text/html;charset=UTF-8 Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit

Dear Cz,

Org D has connected your Patients Know Best (PKB) record to a new team that is, or has been, working with you. The team's name is Team DY.

Why has this happened?
Team DY holds information about you or for you. PKB links you to the team so you can see information about you (such as test results) and information for you (such as library links). In some cases, you can interact with the team (through secure messaging).

Your PKB record is a single place to store information from you, your health professionals and your medical devices. To learn more about PKB, please visit our website.

What happens next?
When you have registered, if Team DY sends you information, PKB will notify you by email.

What if I do not know the Org D or Team DY team?
Sometimes you may see an organisation or team name that is unfamiliar to you. This often happens when health care services share resources for managing their patients' or service users' care. For example, GPs and hospitals sometimes share laboratory systems for your test results, and therefore you may receive data from an organisation you've never been to.

How do I know what information they have about me and what they can see about me?
The information they have about you or for you so far is in your PKB record. You can log in to see it now.

This team is not able to see any other information in your record except information the team has added themselves.

You can change the level of access they have at any time by clicking this link and adjusting their settings, you can read more in the PKB manual.

Please do not reply to this email; this address is not monitored. Log into your record to see your medical information and manage your care.

Yours,

Patients Know Best Help Team
